<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter>
<title>Product measures</title>
<introduction>
<blockquote>
	<p><em><q>Suppose it is said to thee, What is the area of a triangle of side 10 khet and of base 4 khet?</q></em></p>
		<attribution>
			Ahmes
		</attribution>
	
</blockquote>

</introduction>
<section>
<title>Product measures</title>
<p>Given two measure spaces <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> and <m>(Y,\mathcal{N},\nu)</m>, we want to construct a measure on <m>X\times Y</m> from <m>\mu</m> and <m>\nu</m>. We will call this the <em>product measure</em> of <m>\mu</m> and <m>\nu</m>, and denote the product measure by <m>\mu \times \nu</m>. The basic road-map for this construction is simple: if <m>A \in \mathcal{M}</m> and <m>B \in \mathcal{N}</m>, we define <m>(\mu \times \nu)(A\times B) = \mu(A)\nu(B)</m>. We then show that <m>\mu \times \nu</m> is a premeasure on a semiring. Thus, by the Carathéodory-Hahn Theorem (<xref ref="thm-Car-ext-2"/>), <m>\mu\times\nu</m> extends to a measure on <m>X \times Y</m>.</p>
<definition>
	<statement>
		<p>
			Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M})</m> and <m>(Y,\mathcal{N})</m> be two measurable spaces.
	If <m>A \in \mathcal{M}</m> and <m>B \in \mathcal{N}</m>, we call the set <m>A \times B</m> a <em>measurable rectangle</em> in <m>X \times Y</m>.<idx><h>measurable rectangle</h></idx>
		</p>
	</statement>
</definition>
<proposition xml:id="prop-product-premeas">
	<statement>
		<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> and <m>(Y,\mathcal{N},\nu)</m> be measure spaces; let <m>\mathcal{S}</m> be the measurable rectangles in <m>X\times Y</m>; and let <m>\mu \times \nu</m> be the extended real-valued function on <m>\mathcal{S}</m> defined by
<md> (\mu\times\nu)(A\times B) = \mu(A)\nu(B)</md>
for all <m>A \in \mathcal{M}</m> and <m>B \in \mathcal{N}</m>.
	Then <m>\mathcal{S}</m> is a semiring, and <m>\mu \times \nu</m> is a premeasure on <m>\mathcal{S}</m>.</p>
	</statement>

	<proof>
<p>Recall, from <xref ref="exer-product-semiring"/>, that the collection <m>\mathcal{S}</m> of all measurable rectangles in <m>X \times Y</m> forms a semiring of sets.</p>
<p>Note that <m>\emptyset \in \mathcal{S}</m>, and <m>(\mu\times\nu)(\emptyset)=\mu(\emptyset)\nu(\emptyset)=0</m>.
	To show <m>\mu\times \nu</m> is a premeasure it remains to show that <m>\mu\times\nu</m> is finitely additive and countably monotone.</p>
<p>Suppose <m>A \times B</m> is a measurable rectangle such that
<md> A\times B = \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty A_k \times B_k, </md>
where <m>\{A_k \times B_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> are disjoint measurable rectangles.
	For a fixed <m>x \in A</m>, we have
<md> B = \bigcup_{k \colon x \in A_k} B_k. </md>
Note that, if <m>x \in A_{k_1}</m> and <m>x \in A_{k_2}</m>, then since <m>A_{k_1}\times B_{k_1}</m> and <m>A_{k_2}\times B_{k_2}</m> are disjoint, <m>B_{k_1}</m> and <m>B_{k_2}</m> are disjoint.
	Thus, the collection <m>\{B_k\}_{\{k \colon x \in A_k\}}</m> are a disjoint collection of measurable sets is in <m>Y</m>,
	and hence
<md> \nu(B) = \sum_{k \colon x \in A_k} \nu(B_k) = \sum_{k=1}^\infty \nu(B_k)\chi_{A_k}(x).</md>
Hence, for any <m>x \in X</m>,
<md> \nu(B) \chi_A(x) = \sum_{k=1}^\infty \nu(B_k)\chi_{A_k}(x).</md>
Now, by the series version of the Monotone Convergence Theorem, <xref ref="cor-MCT-series"/>,
<md> \mu(A)\nu(B) = \int_X \nu(B) \chi_A \,d\mu= \sum_{k=1}^\infty \int_X\nu(B_k)\chi_{A_k}\,d\mu = \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(A_k)\nu(B_k).</md>
Hence, <m>\mu\times \nu</m> is countably additive, and therefore finitely additive.</p>
<p>Note that, for measurable rectangles <m>A\times B</m> and <m>C \times D</m>,
<md> A \times B \subseteq C \times D </md>
if and only if
<md> A \subseteq C \text{ and } B \subseteq D.</md>
Thus, if <m>A \times B \subseteq C \times D</m>, then
<md> (\mu\times \nu)(A\times B) \leq (\mu\times \nu)(C\times D).</md>
Thus, <m>\mu\times \nu</m> is monotonic.</p>
<p>Let <m>A\times B</m> be a measurable rectangle and <m>\{A_k\times B_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> be measurable rectangles, such that
<md> A\times B \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty A_k \times B_k.</md>
Since the measurable rectangles <m>\mathcal{S}</m> are a semiring, and <m>\mu\times \nu</m> is finitely additive, we can assume that the sets <m>\{A_k \times B_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> are disjoint.
	Thus
<md>
	<mrow>(\mu\times\nu)(A\times B)\amp= (\mu\times\nu)\left(\bigcup_{k=1}^\infty (A\times B)\cap (A_k \times B_k) \right) </mrow>
	<mrow>	\amp= \sum_{k=1}^\infty (\mu\times\nu)\left((A\times B)\cap (A_k \times B_k )\right)</mrow>
	<mrow>	\amp\leq \sum_{k=1}^\infty (\mu\times\nu)(A_k \times B_k).</mrow>
</md>
Hence <m>\mu\times \nu</m> is countably monotone, and therefore <m>\mu\times \nu</m> is a premeasure on the measurable rectangles.</p>
</proof>
</proposition>


<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> and <m>(Y,\mathcal{N},\nu)</m> be two measure spaces, and let <m>(\mu\times\nu)(A\times B)= \mu(A)\nu(B)</m> for <m>A\in \mathcal{M}</m> and <m>B \in \mathcal{N}</m>. By <xref ref="prop-product-premeas"/>, <m>\mu\times\nu</m> is a premeasure on a semiring. Thus, by the Carathéodory-Hahn Theorem (<xref ref="thm-Car-ext-2"/>), <m>\mu\times\nu</m> extends to a measure on <m>(\mu\times\nu)^*</m>-measurable sets in <m>X\times Y</m> (where <m>(\mu\times\nu)^*</m> is the outer measure induced by the premeasure <m>\mu\times\nu</m>). We denote this extension by <m>\mu \times \nu</m>. The measure <m>\mu\times \nu</m> is called the <em>product measure</em><idx><h>measure</h><h>product measure</h></idx> of <m>\mu</m> and <m>\nu</m>.</p>
<remark>
<p>Recall that the Carathéodory-Hahn Theorem does not guarantee uniqueness of the Carathéodory extension.
	In particular, if <m>\mathcal{P}</m> is the collection of <m>\mu\times\nu</m>-measurable sets, we are not guaranteed that <m>\mu\times \nu</m> is the only measure on <m>(X\times Y,\mathcal{P})</m> satisfying
	<md xml:id="eq-prod-meas" number="yes">
		(\mu\times\nu)(A\times B)= \mu(A)\nu(B),
	</md>
	for all <m>A \in \mathcal{M}</m> and <m>B \in \mathcal{N}</m>.</p>
<p>We do have uniqueness when <m>\mu\times\nu</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite on <m>\mathcal{S}</m>.
	In particular, if <m>\mu</m> and <m>\nu</m> are <m>\sigma</m>-finite then <m>\mu\times \nu</m> will be <m>\sigma</m>-finite (<xref ref="exer-sigma-finite-product"/>), and therefore the product measure is the unique measure satisfying  <xref ref="eq-prod-meas"/>.</p>
<p>An example where the product measure is not the unique measure satisfying  <xref ref="eq-prod-meas"/> is given in <xref ref="exer-prod-meas-not-unique"/></p>
</remark>
<remark xml:id="rem-alt-prod-meas">
<p>A word of warning: Some texts define the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra that <m>\mu\times \nu</m> is defined on to be the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra generated by the measurable rectangles. Our definition has <m>\mu\times \nu</m> as a function on the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra of <m>(\mu\times\nu)^*</m>-measurable sets.
	This may be a larger <m>\sigma</m>-algebra.
	<xref ref="exer-product-measurable-sets"/> gives sufficient conditions for when the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra generated by measurable rectangles is smaller than <m>(\mu\times\nu)^*</m>-measurable sets.</p>
<p>We discuss some differences between these different definitions of product measure further in <xref ref="rem-alt-prod-meas-2"/></p>
</remark>
<definition>
	<statement>
	<p>
		Let <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> be non-empty sets and let <m>E \subseteq X\times Y</m>.
		For <m>x \in X</m> the <em><m>x</m>-section</em><idx><h>section</h><h>of a set</h></idx> <m>E_x</m> of <m>E</m> is
		defined as
		<md> E_x = \{y \in Y \colon (x,y) \in E \}.</md>
		For <m>y \in Y</m> the <em><m>y</m>-section</em><idx><h>section</h><h>of a set</h></idx> <m>E^y</m> of <m>E</m> is defined as
		<md> E^y = \{x \in X \colon (x,y) \in E\}.</md>
		If <m>f</m> is a function on <m>X\times Y</m>, and <m>x\in X</m> then the <em><m>x</m>-section</em> <m>f_x</m> of <m>f</m> is a function on <m>Y</m> defined by
		<md> f_x(y)= f(x,y).</md>
		If <m>y\in Y</m> then the <em><m>y</m>-section</em> <m>f^y</m> of <m>f</m> is a function on <m>X</m> defined by
		<md> f^y(x)= f(x,y).</md><idx><h>section</h><h>of a function</h></idx></p>
	</statement>
</definition>
<p>We will prove two theorems relating an integral with respect to a product measure <m>\mu\times\nu</m> and nested integrals with respect to <m>\mu</m> and <m>\nu</m> separately: Fubini's Theorem and Tonelli's Theorem.</p>
<p>We begin with some lemmas. The goal of the following lemmas is to describe <m>(\mu\times \nu)(E)</m> as an integral with respect to <m>\mu</m>. This allows us to (nearly immediately) describe the integrals of simple functions on <m>X\times Y</m>. Then, using simple approximations of measurable functions, we will get the general results needed.</p>
<p>Recall that if <m>\mathcal{R} \subseteq \mathcal{P}(X)</m> is a collection of subsets of a set <m>X</m>, then <m>\mathcal{R}_\sigma</m> is the collection of all countable unions of sets from <m>\mathcal{R}</m>, and <m>\mathcal{R}_{\sigma\delta}</m> is the countable intersection of sets from <m>\mathcal{R}_\sigma</m>.</p>
<lemma xml:id="lem-prod-meas-as-integral">
	<statement>
		
			<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> and <m>(Y,\mathcal{N},\nu)</m> be measure spaces and let <m>\mathcal{S}</m> be the collection of all measurable rectangles in <m>X \times Y</m>.
	If <m>E \in \mathcal{S}_{\sigma\delta}</m> satisfying <m>(\mu\times\nu)(E)&lt;\infty</m>, then the <m>x</m>-section <m>E_x</m> is <m>\nu</m>-measurable for all <m>x \in X</m>, and
<md> (\mu\times\nu)(E) = \int_X \nu(E_x)\,d\mu(x).</md></p>
		
	</statement>

</lemma>
<proof>
<p>Take <m>E \in \mathcal{S}_{\sigma\delta}.</m>
	By <xref ref="exer-product-measurable-sets"/>, <m>E_x</m> is <m>\nu</m>-measurable for all <m>x \in X</m>.
	Alternatively, this can be proved directly by first considering <m>E \in \mathcal{S}</m>, then <m>E \in \mathcal{S}_\sigma</m>, and then <m>E \in \mathcal{S}_{\sigma\delta}</m>.</p>
<p>If <m>E = A\times B \in \mathcal{S}</m> for some <m>A \in \mathcal{M}</m> and <m>B \in \mathcal{N}</m>, then
<md> E_x = \begin{cases} B &amp;\text{if }x \in A\\ \emptyset &amp;\text{if }x \notin A.\end{cases}</md>
Thus
<md> \int_X \nu(E_x)\,d\mu(x) = \int_X \nu(B)\chi_A\,d\mu = \nu(B)\mu(A) = (\mu\times\nu)(E).</md></p>
<p>Now suppose <m>E \in \mathcal{S}_\sigma</m>. 
	Thus, there are measurable rectangles <m>\{A_k\times B_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> such that <m>E = \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty (A_k \times B_k)</m>.
	Since <m>\mathcal{S}</m> is a semiring, we can assume that the sets <m>\{A_k \times B_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> are disjoint.
	Then, for each <m>x \in X</m>, the <m>x</m>-sections <m>\{(A_k\times B_k)_x\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> are disjoint and <m>E_x = \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty(A_k\times B_k)_x</m>.
	Thus, applying the series version of the Monotone Convergence Theorem (Corollar~\ref{cor: MCT series}), we have
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\int_X \nu(E_x)\,d\mu(x) &amp;= \int_X \sum_{k=1}^\infty \nu((A_k\times B_k)_x)\,d\mu(x)\\
		&amp;= \sum_{k=1}^\infty \int_X \nu((A_k\times B_k)_x)\,d\mu(x)\\
		&amp;= \sum_{k=1}^\infty (\mu\times\nu)(A_k \times B_k)\\
		&amp;= (\mu\times\nu)(E).
\end{aligned}
</md></p>
<p>Now suppose that <m>E\in \mathcal{S}_{\sigma\delta}</m> and <m>(\mu\times\nu)(E)&lt;\infty</m>.
	There are <m>\mathcal{S}_\sigma</m> sets <m>\{E_k\}</m> such that <m>E = \bigcap_{k=1}^\infty E_k</m>.
	Since <m>\mathcal{S}</m> is a semiring, we can assume that the sets <m>\{E_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> are descending.
	As <m>(\mu\times\nu)(E)</m> is defined as the outer measure induced by <m>\mu\times\nu</m> on <m>\mathcal{S}</m>, we can further assume that <m>(\mu\times\nu)(E_1)= 0</m>.
	Thus, by the continuity of measure, <m>(\mu\times\nu)(E)= \lim_{k\rightarrow\infty}(\mu\times\nu)(E_k).</m>
	For each <m>x\in X</m> and <m>k</m>, the <m>x</m>-section <m>(E_k)_x</m> is <m>\nu</m>-measurable.
	Hence
<md> E_x = \bigcap_{k=1}^\infty (E_k)_x</md>
is <m>\nu</m>-measurable.
	Further, since
<md> (\mu\times\nu)(E_k)=\int_X \nu((E_k)_x)\,d\mu(x)&lt;\infty,</md>
<m>\nu((E_k)_x)&lt;\infty</m> for almost all <m>x</m>.
	Hence, for almost all <m>x \in X</m>, <m>\nu(E_x)=\lim_{k\rightarrow\infty} \nu((E_k)_x).</m>
	Thus, by the Lebesgue Dominated Convergence Theorem,
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\int_X \nu(E_x)\,d\mu(x) &amp;= \lim_{k\rightarrow\infty} \int_X\nu((E_k)_x)\,d\mu(x)\\
		&amp;= \lim_{k\rightarrow\infty}\nu(E_k)\\
		&amp;= \nu(E).
\end{aligned}
</md></p>
</proof>
<remark>
<p>If <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> and <m>(Y,\mathcal{N},\nu)</m> are <m>\sigma</m>-finite, then conclusion of <xref ref="lem-prod-meas-as-integral"/> holds for any <m>E</m> in the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra generated by the measurable rectangles, not just the <m>\mathcal{S}_{\sigma\delta}</m>-sets of finite measure.
	This is explored in <xref ref="exer-meas-rect-sigma-alg"/>.</p>
</remark>
<lemma xml:id="lem-prod-meas-as-integral-0">
	<statement>
		
			<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> and <m>(Y,\mathcal{N},\nu)</m> be measure spaces with <m>\nu</m> a complete measure.
	If <m>E \subseteq X\times Y</m> is <m>(\mu\times \nu)</m>-measurable with <m>(\mu\times\nu)(E)=0</m>, then the <m>x</m>-section <m>E_x</m> is <m>\nu</m>-measurable for almost all <m>x\in X</m> and <m>\nu(E_x)=0</m>.</p>
		
	</statement>


	<proof>
<p>Take <m>\mu\times\nu</m>-measurable <m>E \subseteq X\times Y</m> with <m>(\mu\times \nu)(E)= 0</m>.
	By <xref ref="prop-sigma-delta-sets"/>, there is a set an <m>\mathcal{S}_{\sigma\delta}</m>-set <m>A</m> such that
	<m>E \subseteq A</m>, and  <m>(\mu\times\nu)(A) = 0</m>.
	Since <m>(\mu\times\nu)(A) = 0&lt;\infty</m>, we can apply <xref ref="lem-prod-meas-as-integral"/>, to get
<md> 0 = (\mu\times\nu)(A) = \int_X \nu(A_x)\,d\mu. </md>
Since the map <m>x \mapsto \nu(A_x)</m> is non-negative, it follows that <m>\nu(A_x)=0</m> for all most all <m>x\in X</m>.
	Since <m>E_x \subseteq A_x</m> for all <m>x\in X</m>, it follows from the completeness of <m>\nu</m> that if <m>\nu(A_x)=0</m> then <m>E_x</m> is <m>\nu</m>-measurable and <m>\nu(A_x)=0</m>.</p>
</proof>
</lemma>

<lemma xml:id="lem-prod-meas-as-integral-general">
	<statement>
		<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> and <m>(Y,\mathcal{N},\nu)</m> be measure spaces with <m>\nu</m> a complete measure.
	If <m>E\subseteq X\times Y</m> is <m>(\mu\times\nu)</m>-measurable with <m>(\mu\times\nu)(E)&lt;\infty</m>,
	then the <m>x</m>-sections <m>E_x</m> are <m>\nu</m>-meaurable for almost all <m>x\in X</m>, and the function <m>x \mapsto \nu(E_x)</m> is a  <m>\mu</m>-measurable function.
	Further,
<md> (\mu\times\nu)(E) = \int_{X} \nu(E_x)\,d\mu(x). </md></p>
	</statement>

	<proof>
<p>
	Since <m>(\mu\times\nu)(E)&lt;\infty</m>, by <xref ref="prop-sigma-delta-sets"/> there is an <m>\mathcal{S}_{\sigma\delta}</m>-set <m>A\subseteq X\times Y</m> such that <m>E \subseteq A</m> and <m>(\mu\times\nu)(E) = (\mu\times\nu)(A)</m>.
	Thus <m>(\mu\times\nu)(A\backslash E)=0</m> by the excision property.</p>
	<p>
		By <xref ref="lem-prod-meas-as-integral"/>, <m>A_x</m> is measurable for all <m>x\in X</m>, and <m>(A\backslash E)_x</m> is measurable for almost all <m>x\in X</m>.
		For each <m>x\in X</m>,
		<md> E_x = A_x \backslash (A\backslash E)_x. </md>
		Thus, for almost all <m>x\in X</m>, <m>E_x</m> is <m>\nu</m>-measurable and
		<md> \nu(A_x) = \nu(E_x) + \nu((A\backslash E)_x)= \nu(E_x).</md>
		Applying <xref ref="lem-prod-meas-as-integral"/> again, we have
<md>
\begin{aligned}
(\mu\times \nu)(E) &amp;= (\mu\times \nu)(A)\\
		&amp;= \int_X\nu(A_x)\,d\mu \\
		&amp;= \int_X\nu(E_x)\,d\mu.
\end{aligned}
</md></p>
</proof>
</lemma>

<theorem xml:id="thm-fubini">
<title>Fubini's Theorem</title>
<statement>
	
		<p><idx><h>Fubini's Theorem</h></idx>
	Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> be a measure space, let <m>(Y,\mathcal{N},\nu)</m> be a complete measure space and let <m>f</m> be a measurable function <m>X\times Y</m> which is integrable with respect to <m>\mu\times \nu</m>.</p>
<p>Then for almost all <m>x\in X</m>, the <m>x</m>-section <m>f_x</m> of <m>f</m> is integrable with respect to <m>\nu</m> and
<md> \int_{X\times Y} f\,d(\mu\times\nu) = \int_X\left(\int_Y f(x,y)\,d\nu(y)\right)d\mu(x).</md></p>
	
</statement>
<proof>
<p>First suppose that <m>f =\chi_E</m> where <m>E\subseteq X\times Y</m> is a measurable set with <m>(\mu\times\nu)(E)&lt;\infty</m>.
	Note that, for each <m>x \in X</m>, the <m>x</m>-section <m>f_x</m> is given by
<md> f_x = \chi_{E_x}. </md>
By <xref ref="lem-prod-meas-as-integral-general"/>, <m>E_x</m> is measurable for almost all <m>x\in X</m>, hence <m>f_x</m> is measurable for almost all <m>x\in X</m>.
	Further, again by <xref ref="lem-prod-meas-as-integral-general"/>,
<md> (\mu\times\nu)(E) = \int_X \nu(E_x)\,d\mu(x) &lt;\infty.</md>
Hence <m>\nu(E_x)&lt;\infty</m> for almost all <m>x\in X</m>.
	Thus, for almost all <m>x\in X</m>,
<md> \infty &gt; \nu(E_x) = \int_Y f_x\,d\mu. </md>
Thus <m>f_x</m> is integrable for almost all <m>x</m>.
	We have now that
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\int_{X\times Y} f\,d(\mu\times \nu)&amp; = (\mu\times\nu)(E)\\
	&amp; = \int_X \nu(E_x)\,d\mu(x)\\&amp; = \int_X\left(\int_Y f(x,y)\,d\nu(y)\right)d\mu(x).
\end{aligned}
</md>
By the linearity of integration, the result holds when <m>f</m> is an integrable simple function on <m>X\times Y</m>.</p>
<p>Now suppose that <m>f</m> is a non-negative integrable function on <m>X \times Y</m>.
	Let <m>(\phi_n)_n</m> be an increasing sequence of simple functions which converge pointwise to <m>f</m>.
	By the above arguments, and the Monotone Convergence Theorem, it follows that
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\int_X\left(\int_Y \phi_n(x,y)\,d\nu(y)\right)\,d\mu(x) &amp;= \lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\int_{X\times Y} \phi_n \,d(\mu\times \nu)\\
		&amp; = \int_{X\times Y} f\,d(\mu\times\nu).
\end{aligned}
</md></p>
<p>To complete the proof we will show that
<md> \lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\int_X\left(\int_Y \phi_n(x,y)\,d\nu(y)\right)\,d\mu(x) = \int_X\left(\int_Y f(x,y)\,d\nu(y)\right)d\mu(x).</md>
By removing a set of measure zero if necessary, we can assume that the <m>x</m>-sections <m>(\phi_n)_x</m> are integrable for all <m>x\in X</m> for all <m>n</m>.
	Thus, for each <m>x\in X</m>, <m>((\phi_n)_x)_n</m> is an increasing sequence of measurable functions, converging pointwise to <m>f_x</m>.
	Thus <m>f_x</m> is measurable for each <m>x\in X</m>.
	For each <m>n</m>, let define a function <m>h_n</m> on <m>X</m> by
<md> h_n(x) = \int_Y (\phi_n)_x\,d\nu,</md>
and define a function <m>h</m> on <m>X</m> by
<md> h(x) = \int_Y f_x\,d\nu.</md>
Since each <m>\phi_n</m> is simple, it follows that <m>h_n</m> is integrable for all <m>n</m>.
	Thus sequence <m>(h_n)_n</m> is an increasing sequence of non-negative measurable functions.
	By the Monotone Covergenece Theorem applied to <m>((\phi_n)_x)_n</m>, <m>(h_n)_n</m> converges pointwise to <m>h</m>.
	Applying the Monotone Convergence Theorem to the sequence <m>(h_n)_n</m>, we get
<md> \lim_{n\rightarrow\infty}\int_X h_n \,d\mu = \int_X h\,d\mu;</md>
i.e.
<md> \lim_{n\rightarrow\infty} \int_X \left(\int_Y \phi_n(x,y)\,d\nu(y) \right)\,d\mu(x) = \int_X \left(\int_Y f(x,y)\,d\nu(y) \right)\,d\mu(x).</md></p>
<p>If <m>f</m> is an arbitrary integrable function on <m>X\times Y</m>, then <m>f = f_+ - f_-</m> where <m>f_+</m> is the positive part of <m>f</m>, and <m>f_-</m> is the negative part of <m>f</m>.
	Since the result holds for <m>f_+</m> and <m>f_-</m>, the result holds for <m>f</m> by the linearity of integration.</p>
</proof>
</theorem>

<remark xml:id="rem-fubini">
<p>Let <m>f</m> be a measurable function on a product space <m>X\times Y</m>.
Note that, in order to apply Fubini's theorem, we must first know that <m>f</m> is integrable with repsect to the product measure <m>\mu \times \nu</m>.
It is possible that the iterated integral
<md> \int_X \left( \int_Y f(x,y)\,d\nu(y)\right) \,d\mu(x)</md>
exists and is finite, but <m>f</m> itself is not integral with resepct to <m>\mu \times \nu</m>.
An example is given in <xref ref="exer-failure-of-fubini"/>.</p>
</remark>
<p>The shortcoming of Fubini's Theorem discussed in <xref ref="rem-fubini"/> does not arise when when we deal exclusively with <m>\sigma</m>-finite measure spaces. This is the famed theorem of Tonelli.</p>

<theorem xml:id="thm-tonelli">
<title>Tonelli's Theorem</title>
<statement>
	<p>
		<idx><h>Tonelli's Theorem</h></idx>
	Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> and <m>(Y,\mathcal{N},\nu)</m> be <m>\sigma</m>-finite measure spaces, with <m>\nu</m> a complete measure, and let <m>f</m> be a non-negative <m>(\mu\times\nu)</m>-measurable function on <m>X\times Y</m>.
	Then, for almost all <m>x\in X</m>, the <m>x</m>-section <m>f_x</m> of <m>f</m> is <m>\nu</m>-measurable, and the (almost everywhere defined) function on <m>X</m>
<md> x \mapsto \int_Y f_x\,d\nu</md>
is <m>\mu</m>-measurable.
	Further,
<md> \int_{X \times Y}f\,d(\mu\times \nu) = \int_X \left( \int_Y f(x,y)\,d\nu(y)\right) \,d\mu(x).</md>
	</p>
</statement>

	<proof>
<p>Since, <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> and <m>(Y,\mathcal{N},\nu)</m> are <m>\sigma</m>-finite, the product measure <m>\mu \times \nu</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite on <m>X\times Y</m>, by <xref ref="exer-sigma-finite-product"/>.
	Thus, by the Simple Approximation Theorem, <xref ref="thm-simple-approx"/>, there is an increasing sequence of simple functions <m>(\phi_n)_n</m> which converge pointwise to <m>f</m> and each <m>\phi_n</m> is supported in a set of finite measure.
	For each <m>n</m>, since <m>\phi_n</m> is a supported in a set of finite measure, <m>\phi_n</m> is integrable with respect to <m>\mu\times \nu</m>.
	Hence, we can apply Fubini's Theorem to each function <m>\phi_n</m>, to get
<md> \int_{X\times Y}{\phi_n}\,d{(\mu\times\nu)} = \int_{X}{\left(\intd{Y}\,d{\phi_n(x,y)}{\nu(y)}\right)}{\mu(x)}.</md>
The rest of the proof proceeds in a similar vein to that of Fubini's Theorem.</p>
</proof>
</theorem>

<p>With obvious modifications, replacing <m>x</m>-sections with <m>y</m>-sections, we can prove the analogous results of Fubini's Theorem and Tonelli's Theorem on <m>X\times Y</m>, for measure space <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> and <m>(Y,\mathcal{N},\nu)</m> when <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> is complete. Fubini's Theorem and Tonelli's Theorem are often combined into one result, the Fubini-Tonelli Theorem, which combines the two results.</p>
<theorem xml:id="thm-fubini-tonelli">
<title>The Fubini-Tonelli Theorem</title>
<statement>
	<p>
		<idx><h>Fubini's Theorem</h><h>The Fubini-Tonelli Theorem</h></idx><idx><h>Tonelli's Theorem</h><see>Fubini's Theorem</see></idx>
	Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> and <m>(Y,\mathcal{N},\nu)</m> be <m>\sigma</m>-finite complete measure spaces, and let <m>f</m> be a <m>(\mu\times\nu)</m>-measurable function on <m>X\times Y</m>.
	Then
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\int_{X\times Y}{|f|}\,d{(\mu\times\nu)} &amp;= \int_{X}{\left(\intd{Y}\,d{|f(x,y)|}{\nu(y)}\right)}{\mu(x)}\\
		 &amp;= \int_{Y}{\left(\intd{X}\,d{|f(x,y)|}{\mu(x)}\right)}{\nu(y)}.
\end{aligned}
</md>
Further, if any of the three integrals above are finite, then <m>f</m> is integrable and
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\int_{X\times Y}{f}\,d{(\mu\times\nu)} &amp;= \int_{X}{\left(\intd{Y}\,d{f(x,y)}{\nu(y)}\right)}{\mu(x)}\\
		&amp;= \int_{Y}{\left(\intd{X}\,d{f(x,y)}{\mu(x)}\right)}{\nu(y)}.
\end{aligned}
</md>
	</p>
</statement>
</theorem>

<remark xml:id="rem-alt-prod-meas-2">
<p>We note in <xref ref="rem-alt-prod-meas"/>, that some people only define the product measure to act on the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra generated by the measurable rectangles.
	Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> and <m>(Y,\mathcal{N},\nu)</m> be <m>\sigma</m>-finite measure spaces, let <m>\mu \times \nu</m> be the product measure on <m>X\times Y</m>, and let <m>\pi</m> be the restriction of <m>\mu\times \nu</m> be the restriction of <m>\mu \times \nu</m> to the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra <m>\mathcal{F}</m> generated by the measurable rectangles.
	The analogue of Fubini's Theorem<fn>We will not prove this version of Fubini's Theorem.
		If you wish you can prove it using <xref ref="exer-product-measurable-sets"/> and similar arguments to how we proved <xref ref="thm-fubini"/>.</fn> for <m>\pi</m> states: if <m>f</m> is integrable with respect to <m>\pi</m>, then the <m>x</m>-sections <m>f_x</m> are integrable with respect to <m>\nu</m> for all <m>x \in X</m>, and
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\int_{X\times Y}{f}\,d{\pi} &amp;= \int_{X}{\left(\intd{Y}\,d{f(x,y)}{\nu(y)}\right)}{\mu(x)}\\
	&amp;= \int_{Y}{\left(\intd{X}\,d{f(x,y)}{\mu(x)}\right)}{\nu(y)}.
\end{aligned}
</md>
The key differences between Fubini's Theorem for <m>\mu \times \nu</m> (<em>our</em> version) and for <m>\pi</m> are
<ol>
<li>we do not need to assume that <m>\nu</m> or <m>\mu</m> is a complete measure to prove Fubini's Theorem for <m>\mu\times\nu</m>;
</li>
<li>we have that <m>f_x</m> is <m>\nu</m>-integrable for all <m>x\in X</m>, not just for almost all <m>x \in X</m>, in Fubini's Theorem for <m>\pi</m>; and
</li>
<li>we are assuming that the measure spaces are <m>\sigma</m>-finite in Fubini's Theorem for <m>\pi</m>.
</li>
</ol>
In practice, concerns over these differences rarely matter.
	For <em><sq>nice</sq></em> functions and <em><sq>nice</sq></em> <m>\sigma</m>-algebras one usually has that
<md> \int_{X\times Y}{f}\,d{(\mu\times\nu)} = \int_{X\times Y}{f}\,d{\pi}. </md></p>
</remark>

<subsection xml:id="sec-products-three-or-more">
<title>Products of three or more measures</title>
<p>
	If <m>\{(X_k,\M_k,\mu_k)\}_{k=1}^n</m> are a collection of $n$ measure spaces, we define the <em>measurable rectangles</em><idx><h>measurable rectangles</h></idx> in <m>X = \prod_{k=1}^n X_k</m> as the sets
<md> \left\{\prod_{k=1}^N A_k \colon A_k \in \mathcal{M}_k\, \text{for }k=1,\ldots,n \right\}.</md>
We can similarly define a product measure on <m>X</m>. We leave the details of the next proposition to the exercises, <xref ref="exer-measurable-rectangles-2" /> and <xref ref="exer-n-dim-prod-measure"/>.</p>
<proposition xml:id="prop-n-dim-prod-measure">
	<statement>
<p>Let <m>\{(X_k,\mathcal{M}_k,\mu_k)\}_{k=1}^n</m> be measure spaces, let <m>\mathcal{S}</m> be the measurable rectangles in <m>\prod_{k=1}^n X_k</m>; and let <m>\mu_1 \times \ldots \mu_n</m> be the extended real-valued function on <m>\mathcal{S}</m> defined by
<md> (\mu_1 \times \ldots \times \mu_n)(A_1\times \ldots \times A_n) = \mu_1(A_1)\mu_2(A_2)\ldots \mu_n(A_n)</md>
for <m>A_k \in \mathcal{M}_k</m> for <m>1\leq k \leq n</m>.
	Then <m>\mathcal{S}</m> is a semiring, and <m>\mu_1\times\ldots\times \mu_n</m> is a premeasure on <m>\mathcal{S}</m>.</p>
</statement>
</proposition>

<p>By <xref ref="prop-n-dim-prod-measure"/>, we can thus extend <m>\mu_1\times\ldots\times \mu_n</m> to a measure on <m>\prod_{k=1}^n X_k</m> by the Carathéodory-Hahn Theorem. This measure is also called the <em>product measure</em>.<idx><h>product measure</h></idx> Just as in the <m>n=2</m> case, it is not guaranteed that the measure <m>\mu_1\times\ldots\times \mu_n</m> is the unique extension of the its restriction to the measurable rectangles. However, when each measure space <m>(X_k,\mathcal{M}_k,\mu_k)</m> is a <m>\sigma</m>-finite measure space, for <m>1\leq k \leq n</m>, then we do have uniqueness. The uniqueness results also gives the following associativity result.</p>
<proposition xml:id="prop-n-dim-prod-measure-associative">
	<statement>
		<p>
			Let <m>(X_1,\mathcal{M}_1,\mu_1)</m>, <m>(X_2,\mathcal{M}_2,\mu_2)</m>, and <m>(X_3,\mathcal{M}_3,\mu_3)</m> be <m>\sigma</m>-finite measure spaces. Then
<md> \mu_1 \times \mu_2 \times \mu_3 =(\mu_1 \times \mu_2) \times \mu_3 =\mu_1 \times (\mu_2 \times \mu_3).</md>
		</p>
	</statement>
</proposition>
</subsection>
</section>

<section xml:id="sec-lebesgue-measure-on-Rn">
	<title>Lebesgue measure on <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m></title>
	
<definition>
	<statement>
		<p>Let <m>m</m> be the Lebesgue measure on the Lebesgue measurable subsets of <m>\mathbb{R}</m> and let <m>n\geq 1</m>.
		Let <m>m_n</m> be the product measure
		<md> m_n = \underbrace{m \times \ldots \times m}_{n\ \text{times}} </md>
		on <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
		We call <m>m_n</m> the <em>Lebesgue measure on <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m></em>.<idx><h>Lebesgue measure</h><h>on <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m></h></idx>
		The <m>\sigma</m>-algebra of subsets which are measurable with respect to <m>m_n</m> are the <em>Lebesgue measurable subsets of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m></em>.<idx><h>measurable set</h><h>Lebesgue measurable set</h></idx></p>

		<p>
		Denote by <m>m_n^*</m> the outer measure induced by 
		<md> \underbrace{m \times \ldots \times m}_{n\ \text{times}} </md>
		on the measurable rectangles.
		We call <m>m_n^*</m> the <em>Lebesgue outer measure</em> on <m>\bR^n</m>. <idx><h>outer measure</h><h>Lebesgue outer measure</h><h>on <m>\bR^n</m></h> </idx>
		</p>
	</statement>
</definition>

<p>Note that, since the Lebesgue measure <m>m</m> on <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite on <m>\mathbb{R}</m>, <m>m_n</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite on <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>. Further, by inductive application of <xref ref="prop-n-dim-prod-measure-associative"/>, if <m>k</m> and <m>l</m> are positive integers such that <m>k+l = n</m>, then <m>m_n = m_k \times m_l</m>. Thus the following version of the Fubini-Tonelli Theorem follows from <xref ref="thm-fubini-tonelli"/>.</p>
<theorem>
<title>The Fubini-Tonelli Theorem on <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m></title>
<p><idx><h>Fubini's Theorem</h><h>The Fubini-Tonelli Theorem</h></idx><idx><h>Tonelli's Theorem</h><see>Fubini's Theorem</see></idx>
	Let <m>k,l,n</m> be non-negative integers with <m>n = k + l</m> and let <m>f</m> be a Lebesgue measurable function on <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
	Then
<md> \intd{\mathbb{R}^n}{|f|}{m_n} = \intd{\mathbb{R}^k}{\intd{\mathbb{R}^l}{|f|}{m_l}}{m_k} \intd{\mathbb{R}^l}{\intd{\mathbb{R}^k}{|f|}{m_k}}{m_l}.</md>
If any of these values are finite, then <m>f</m> is integrable with respect to <m>m_n</m> and
<md> \intd{\mathbb{R}^n}{f}{m_n} = \intd{\mathbb{R}^k}{\intd{\mathbb{R}^l}{f}{m_l}}{m_k} \intd{\mathbb{R}^l}{\intd{\mathbb{R}^k}{f}{m_k}}{m_l}.</md></p>
</theorem>

<p>
	One can define the Lebesgue measure on <m>\bR^n</m> directly, without using products of the Lebesgue measure on <m>\bR</m>.
	We can, instead define the Lebesgue measure on <m>\bR^n</m> akin to how the Lebesgue measure was defined on <m>\bR</m>.
	That is, we can define a premeasure on a nice semiring of subsets of <m>\bR^n</m> that extends to a measure on <m>\bR^n</m>. 
	This nice semiring will be smaller than the measureable rectangles, and defining it does not require direct knowledge of the Lebesgue measure on <m>\bR</m>.
	We will not give the full details of this construction; we do not need the full details as we have already defined the Lebesgue measure on <m>\bR^n</m>, but one can deduce from the next proposition what is needed.
	We will first define the sets in the nice semiring: <em>intervals</em>. 
	We will not need to know that it is a semiring, so will not prove that.
</p>

<definition xml:id="def-intervals">
	<statement>
		<p>
			Fix <m>n \geq 1</m>.<idx><h>interval</h><h>of <m>\bR^n</m></h></idx>
			A set <m>I \subseteq \bR^n</m> is an <em>interval of <m>\bR^n</m></em> if there are intervals <m>I_1,\ldots,I_n\subseteq \bR</m> such that
			<md> I = I_1 \times \ldots \times I_n </md></p>
			<p>
			An interval <m>I\subseteq\bR^n</m> is called an <em>open</em> interval if each <m>I_i</m> is open for <m>i=1,\ldots,n</m>.
		</p>
	</statement>
</definition>

<remark>
	<p>
		Note that if <m>I\subseteq \bR^n</m> is an interval, then <m>I</m> is a measurable rectangle.
		In fact when <m>n=2</m>, <m>I</m> will actually look like a rectangle.
		It could thus be argued that what we are calling <sq>intervals</sq> should be called <sq>measurable rectangles</sq>, and <sq>measurable rectangles</sq> should be called something else.
		We will, however, stick with the terminology established, even if it makes us a little uncomfortable.
	</p>
</remark>

<p>
	We will now show that we can work with intervals in place of measurable intervals, thus Lebesgue measure on <m>\bR^n</m> could be defined in terms of intervals instead of measurable rectangles.	
</p>

<proposition xml:id="prop-intervals">
	<statement>
		<p>
			For each <m>E \subseteq \bR^n</m>
		<md>
			<mrow> m_n^*(E) = \inf \left\{ \sum_{k=1}^n m_n(I_k) \colon \{I_k\}_{k=1}^\infty \text{ open intervals in }\bR^n,\ E\subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty I_k \right\}. </mrow>
		</md></p>
	</statement>
</proposition>

<proof>
	<p>
		By definition of the Lebesgue outer measure
		<md>
			m_n^*(E) = \inf \left\{ \sum_{k=1}^n m_n(I_k) \colon \{R_k\}_{k=1}^\infty \text{ measurable rectangles},\ E\subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty R_k \right\}.
		</md>
		Thus,
		<md>
			m_n^*(E) \leq\inf \left\{ \sum_{k=1}^n m_n(I_k) \colon \{I_k\}_{k=1}^\infty \text{ open intervals in }\bR^n,\ E\subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty I_k \right\}.
		</md>
		The result, therefore, holds if <m>m_n^*(E)=\infty</m>.
		We can thus assume that <m>m_n^*(E)&lt;\infty</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
		Suppose now that <m>E = A_1\times\ldots\times A_n</m> where each <m>A_k \subseteq \bR</m> is a Lebesgue measurable set of finte measure.
		That is, assume that <m>E</m> is a measurable rectangle with finite measure.
		Fix <m>\varepsilon &gt; 0</m>. By repeated applications of <xref ref="thm-Leb-meas-sets-G-delta-F-sigma"/> we can find open subsets <m>U_k \subseteq \bR</m> with <m>A_k \subseteq U_k</m> for <m>k=1,\ldots,n</m> such that
		<md>
			<mrow>m(U_n\backslash A_n) \amp &lt; \frac{\varepsilon}{n\cdot(m(A_1)m(A_2)\ldots m(A_{n-1}) + 1)}, </mrow>
			<mrow>m(U_{n-1}\backslash A_{n-1}) \amp &lt; \frac{\varepsilon}{n\cdot(m(A_1)m(A_2)\ldots m(A_{n-2})m(U_n)) + 1)}, </mrow>
			<mrow>m(U_{n-2}\backslash A_{n-2}) \amp &lt; \frac{\varepsilon}{n\cdot(m(A_1)m(A_2)\ldots m(A_{n-3})m(U_{n-1})m(U_n)) + 1)}, </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp \vdots </mrow>
			<mrow>m(U_{1}\backslash A_{1}) \amp &lt; \frac{\varepsilon}{n\cdot(m(U_2)m(U_3)\ldots m(U_n)) + 1)}. </mrow>
		</md>
		Let <m>U = U_1\times\ldots\times U_k</m>. 
		Since each open subset of <m>\bR</m> is a countable union of disjoint intervals, <m>U</m> is a countable union of disjoint intervals in <m>\bR^n</m>.
		Further, <m>E \subseteq U</m>.
	</p>

	<p>
		We will bound <m>m_n(U\backslash I)</m>.
		Note that we can write <m>U\backslash E</m> as the (disjoint) union <fn>Note that this calculation is most of what is needed to show that the intervals in <m>\bR^n</m> form a semiring.</fn>
		<md>
			<mrow>E\backslash U = \amp [(U_1\backslash A_1)\times U_2 \times \ldots \times U_n]  </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp \cup [A_1\times (U_2\backslash A_2) \times U_3\times \ldots \times U_n]  </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp \vdots </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp \cup [A_1\times A_2 \times  \ldots \times A_{n-1}\times (U_n\backslash A_n)].  </mrow>
		</md>
		Thus, <m>m_n(U\backslash E) &lt; \varepsilon</m>.
		Hence, by the <xref ref="prop-measure-properties" text="custom">excision property</xref>,
		<md> m_n(E) &gt; m_n(U) -\varepsilon. </md>
		Since <m>\varepsilon>0</m>  was arbitrary, and <m>U</m> is a countable union of disjoint intervals in <m>\bR^n</m>, the result now follows for measurable rectangles.
	</p>
	<p>
		Finally, if <m>m_n^*(E)&lt; \infty</m> and <m>\varepsilon &gt; 0 </m>, then there is a countable collection of measurable rectangles <m>\{R_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> with <m>E \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty R_k</m> and
		<md>
			m_n^*(E) &gt; \sum_{k=1}^\infty m_n(R_k) - \varepsilon/2.
		</md>
		By the above argument, for each <m>k</m> there is a countable collection <m>\{I^k_i\}_{i=1}^\infty</m> of intervals in <m>\bR^n</m> such that
		<md>
			m_n(R_k) &gt; \sum_{i=1}^\infty m_n(I^k_i) -\frac{\varepsilon}{2^{k+1}}.
		</md>
		Thus
		<md>
			<mrow>m_n^*(E) &gt; \amp \sum_{k=1}^\infty m_n(R_k) - \varepsilon/2 </mrow>
			<mrow> &gt; \amp \sum_{k=1}^\infty \sum_{i=1}^\infty m_n(I^k_i) - \varepsilon. </mrow>
		</md>
		Hence 
		<md number="no">
			<mrow> m_n^*(E) = \inf \left\{ \sum_{k=1}^n m_n(I_k) \colon \{I_k\}_{k=1}^\infty \text{ open intervals in }\bR^n,\ E\subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty I_k \right\}, </mrow>
		</md>
		as desired.
	</p>
</proof>

<p>
	<xref ref="prop-intervals"/> allows us to work with intervals in <m>\bR^n</m> in place of measurable rectangles.
	Intervals have the advantage that we understand them.
	We know a lot about Lebesgue measurable sets in <m>\bR</m>, but we also know enough to know that they are sometimes quite strange, e.g. <xref ref="lem-non-Borel"/>.
</p>

<p>We will see that the Lebesgue measure on <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> has similar properties to the Lebesgue measure on <m>\mathbb{R}</m>. We first note that all Borel sets in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> are Lebesgue measurable.</p>
<p>We will recall what the Borel subsets of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> are. A subset <m>U \subseteq \mathbb{R}^n</m> is <em>open</em> if given <m>x \in U</m>, there is a <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m> such that
<md> \{ y \in \mathbb{R}^n \colon \|x-y\|_2 &lt; \varepsilon \} \subseteq U.</md>
We are using the Euclidean/<m>2</m>-norm on <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> here; this is the usual and more intuitive way to define open subsets of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>. However, the choice of the <m>2</m>-norm is immaterial. It follows from <xref ref="thm-equiv-norms-on-Rn"/> that the following statements are equivalent for a subset <m>U \subseteq \mathbb{R}^n</m>:
<ol>
<li><m>U</m> is an open subset of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>;
</li>
<li>given <m>x \in U</m>, there is a <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m> such that <m>\{ y \in \mathbb{R}^n \colon \|x-y\|_p &lt; \varepsilon \} \subseteq U</m> for some <m>p</m> with <m>1\leq p \leq \infty</m>;
</li>
<li>given <m>x \in U</m>, for each <m>p</m>, <m>1\leq p \leq \infty</m>, there is an <m>\varepsilon_p&gt;0</m> such that <m>\{ y \in \mathbb{R}^n \colon \|x-y\|_p &lt; \varepsilon_p \} \subseteq U</m>.
</li>
</ol>
That is, to see if a set <m>U \subseteq \mathbb{R}^n</m> is open, it does not matter which <m>p</m>-norm we use. The Borel sets in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> are the members of the smallest <m>\sigma</m>-algebra of subsets of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> which contains all open subsets of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>. We denote the Borel sets in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> by <m>\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R}^n)</m>.<idx><h>Borel sets</h><h>in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m></h></idx> We leave the details of the following proposition as an exercise, <xref ref="exer-borel-in-Rn"/>. The result should be compared to <xref ref="thm-Borel-Lebesgue-meas"/>.</p>
<proposition xml:id="prop-borel-in-Rn">
<p>Let <m>B</m> be a Borel subset of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>, then <m>B</m> is Lebesgue measurable.</p>
</proposition>
<p>Another important property that the Lebesgue measure <m>m_n</m> shares with the Lebesgue measure <m>m</m> on <m>\mathbb{R}</m> is translation invariance.
The proof of this follows (almost) immediately from the <m>n = 1</m> case.
</p>
<proposition>
<p>Let <m>n</m> be a non-negative integer, let <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}^n</m> be a Lebesgue measurable set,  let <m>v</m> be a vector in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>, and
	let
<md> A + v = \{x+ y \colon x \in A \}.</md>
Then <m>m_n(A) = m_n(A+v)</m>.</p>
</proposition>

<p>
The Lebesgue measure on <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> also has regularity properties analogous to those of the Lebesgue measure on <m>\mathbb{R}</m>. 
The following two results should be compared to <xref ref="thm-Leb-meas-sets-G-delta-F-sigma"/> and <xref ref="thm-Lebesgue-regular"/>.
We omit the proofs.
Arguments similar to the <m>1</m>-dimensional cases can be used, with the aide of <xref ref="prop-intervals"/>.
</p>

<theorem xml:id="thm-Lebesgue-regular-n">
	<title>Regularity of Lebesgue measure on <m>\bR^n</m></title>
	<statement>
		<p>
			Let <m>E \subseteq \bR^n</m> be a Lebesgue measurable set. Then
			<md>
				m_n(E) = \inf\{m_n(U) \colon E \subseteq U,\ U\text{ open}\},
			</md>
			and
			<md>
				m_n(E) = \inf\{m_n(K) \colon K \subseteq E,\ K \text{ compact}\}.
			</md>
			<idx><h>regularity of a measure</h><h>regularity of Lebesgue measure on <m>\bR^n</m></h></idx>
		</p>
	</statement>
</theorem>

<corollary xml:id="cor-Leb-meas-sets-G-delta-F-sigma">
	<statement>
		<p>
				Let <m>E \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>.
				The following are equivalent.
			<ol>
			<li><m>E</m> is Lebesgue measurable;
			</li>
			<li>for every <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m> there exists an open set <m>U</m> containing <m>E</m> such that <m>m^*(U\backslash E) &lt; \varepsilon</m>;
			</li>
			<li>there is a <m>G_\delta</m>-set <m>G</m> contraing <m>E</m> such that <m>m^*(G\backslash E) = 0</m>;
			</li>
			<li>for every <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m> there exists a closed set <m>C</m> contained in <m>E</m> such that <m>m^*(E\backslash C) &lt; \varepsilon</m>;
			</li>
			<li>there is an <m>F_\sigma</m>-set <m>F</m> contained in <m>E</m> such that <m>m^*(E\backslash F) = 0</m>.
			</li>
			</ol>
		</p>
	</statement>
</corollary>
</section>

<section>
	<title>Change of variables</title>
<p>In this section we will study how changes of variables in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> effect the integral. We begin by noting that all linear maps from <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> to <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> are continuous.</p>

<lemma xml:id="lem-linear-cont">
	<statement>
		<p>
			Let <m>T \colon \mathbb{R}^n \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^n</m> be a linear map. Then <m>T</m> is continuous.
		</p>
	</statement>

	<proof>
<p>Let <m>e_1,\ldots,e_n</m> be the canonical basis of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
	That is, let <m>e_1= (1,0,\ldots,0)</m>, <m>e_2 = (0,1,0,\ldots,0)</m>, and so on.
	Take <m>x = (x_1,\ldots,x_n) \in \mathbb{R}^n</m>.
	Then
<md>

	<mrow> \|T(x)\|_2 \amp= \| x_1 T(e_1) + \ldots + x_nT(e_n)\|_2 </mrow>
	<mrow>	\amp\leq \sum_{k=1}^n |x_k| \|T(e_k)\|_2 </mrow>
	<mrow>	\amp\leq \left(\sum_{k=1}^n\|T(e_k)\|_2^2\right)^{1/2} \|x\|_2,</mrow>

</md>
where the last inequality is an application of the <xref ref="exer-Cauchy-Schwarz-Rn" text="custom"> Cauchy-Schwarz inequality</xref>.
	Letting <m>M = \left(\sum_{k=1}^n\|T(e_k)\|_2^2\right)^{1/2}</m>, we have shown that <m>\|T(x)\|_2 \leq M \|x\|_2</m> for all <m>x \in \mathbb{R}^n</m>.
	Hence, by <xref ref="prop-bounded-cont"/>, <m>T</m> is continuous.
		</p>
</proof>
</lemma>

<remark>
	<p>
		Recall that the norm of a linear functional <m>\phi</m> on a normed vector space <m>X</m> is defined as
		<md>
			\|\phi\|_\mathrm{op} = \inf\{M \colon |\phi(x)|\leq M \|x\| \text{ for all } x \in X \}.
		</md>
		We can use <xref ref="lem-linear-cont"/> to similarly define a norm on the space of linear maps from <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> to <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
		That is, if <m>T</m> is a linear map from <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> to <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> we can define <m>\|T\|_\mathrm{op}</m> as
		<md>
			\|T\|_\mathrm{op} = \inf\{M \colon \|T(x)\|_2 \leq M \|x\|_2 \text{ for all } x \in \mathbb{R}^n\}.
		</md>
		We will not not make too much use of the fact that this is a norm in these notes, but it plays an important role in functional analysis.
		<idx><h>norm</h><h>on linear maps</h></idx>
	</p>
</remark>

<p>If <m>f</m> is a Lebesgue integrable function on <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>, and <m>T</m> is an invertible linear map on <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>, we want to compare the integrals <m>\intd{\mathbb{R}^n}{f}{m_n}</m> and <m>\intd{\mathbb{R}^n}{f\circ T}{m_n}</m>. It is not (yet) clear that the second integral is defined. In general, the composition of a measurable function and a continuous function need not be continuous. <fn>Note that we can not apply <xref ref="prop-comp-meas"/> here.</fn> Thus, in order to proceed, we must first show that <m>f \circ T</m> is measurable.
As we are ultimately interested in the case when <m>T</m> is an invertible linear map, we will restrict to this case (though conclusions of <xref ref="lem-meas-of-interval"/>, <xref ref="lem-lin-meas"/>, and <xref ref="prop-comp-meas-linear"/> hold for all linear maps).</p>

<p>Let <m>e_1,\ldots,e_n</m> be the standard orthonormal basis of <m>\bR^n</m>.
Recall that if <m>T</m> is an invertible linear map in <m>\bR^n</m>, then <m>T</m> can be written as product of matrices of the form:<fn>We are just using the fact that any invertible matrix can be row-reduced to the identity matrix.</fn>
<dl>
<li xml:id="li-type1"><title>Type 1</title>there is an <m>i</m> such that <m>Te_i = ce_i</m> for some real <m>c\neq 0</m>, and <m>Te_j = e_j</m> for all <m>j\neq i</m>;
</li>
<li xml:id="li-type2"><title>Type 2</title>there is an <m>i &lt; n</m> such that <m>Te_i = e_i + e_{i+1}</m>, and <m>Te_k = e_k</m> for all <m>k\neq i</m>;
</li>
<li xml:id="li-type3"><title>Type 3</title> there is an <m>i &lt; n</m> such that <m>Te_i = e_{i+1}</m>, <m>Te_{i+1} = e_i</m>, and <m>Te_k = e_k</m> for all <m>k\neq i,i+1</m>.</li>
</dl>
Note that, if <m>T</m> is of <xref ref="li-type1" text="custom">Type 1</xref>, then <m>\det(T) = c</m>, if <m>T</m> is of <xref ref="li-type2" text="custom">Type 2</xref>, then <m>\det(T) = 1</m>, and if <m>T</m> is of <xref ref="li-type3" text="custom">Type 3</xref>, then <m>\det(T) = -1</m>.
</p>

<lemma xml:id="lem-meas-of-interval">
	<statement>
		<p>
			Let <m>T \colon \mathbb{R}^n \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^n</m> be an invertible linear map.
			Then
			<md>
				m_n^*(T(E)) \leq |\det(T)| m_n^*(E)
			</md>
			for all <m>E \subseteq \mathbb{R}^n</m>.
		</p>
	</statement>
	<proof>
		<p>
			Let <m>I = I_1 \times \ldots \times I_n</m> be an interval in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
			If <m>T</m> is of <xref ref="li-type1" text="custom">Type 1</xref> for some non-zero constant <m>c</m>, then <m>T(I)</m> is an interval and <m>m_n(T(I)) = |c| m_n(I) = |\det(T)| m_n(I)</m>.
			Similarly, if <m>T</m> is of <xref ref="li-type2" text="custom">Type 3</xref>, then <m>T(I)</m> is an interval and <m>m_n(T(I)) = m_n(I) = |\det(T)| m_n(I)</m>.
		</p>

		<p>	
			Suppose <m>T</m> is of <xref ref="li-type2" text="custom">Type 2</xref> and <m>n=2</m>.
			As <m>T</m> is linear, we can assume that <m>I = [0,a]\times[0,b]</m> for some <m>a,b\geq 0</m>.
			Then
			<md>
				T(I) = \{ (x,y) \colon 0\leq x \leq a,\ ax \leq y \leq ax + b\}
			</md>
			is a parallelogram in <m>\bR^2</m>.
			By <xref ref="exer-triangle"/>, <m>T(I)</m> is measurable and
			<md>
				m_2(T(I)) =ab = m_2(I).
			</md>
			Note that, if <m>n &gt; 2</m>  and <m>T</m> is of <xref ref="li-type2" text="custom">Type 2</xref>, then <m>T</m> only changes on the <m>i</m> and <m>i+1</m> coordinates of an <m>x \in \bR^n</m>, and leaves all other coordinates fixed.
			Thus, by the <m>n = 2</m> case, <m>T(I)</m> is measurable and <m>m_n(T(I)) = m_n(I) = |\det(T)| m_n(I)</m>.
		</p>

		<p>
			Suppose now, that <m>T</m> is of <xref ref="li-type1" text="custom">Type 1</xref>, <xref ref="li-type2" text="custom">Type 2</xref>, or <xref ref="li-type3" text="custom">Type 3</xref>.
			Take any <m>E \subseteq \bR^n</m> with <m>m_n^*(E)&lt;\infty</m>.
			Let <m>\{I_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> be a countable collection of intervals in <m>\bR^n</m> such that <m>E \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty I_k</m>.
			Then
			<md>
				<mrow>m_n^*(T(E)) \amp \leq \sum_{k=1}^\infty m_n(T(I_k)) </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = |\det(T)| \sum_{k=1}^\infty m_n(I_k). </mrow>
			</md>
			Taking an infimum over all such collections of intervals, we have that <m>m_n^*(T(E)) \leq |\det(T)| m_n^*(E)</m>.
		</p>

		<p>
			Now suppose that <m>T</m> is an arbitrary invertible linear map on <m>\bR^n</m>.
			Then <m>T = T_1\ldots T_k</m> where each <m>T_i</m> is of <xref ref="li-type1" text="custom">Type 1</xref>, <xref ref="li-type2" text="custom">Type 2</xref>, or <xref ref="li-type3" text="custom">Type 3</xref>.
			Thus, for <m>E \subseteq \bR^n</m>
			<md>
				<mrow>m_n^*(T(E)) \amp \leq |\det(T_1)| m_n^*(T_2T_3\ldots T_k (E)) </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp \leq |\det(T_1)| \ldots|det(T_k)| m_n^*(E) </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = |\det(T)| m_n^*(E), </mrow>
			</md>
			completing the proof.
		</p>
	</proof>
</lemma>

<lemma xml:id="lem-lin-meas">
	<statement>
		<p>
			Let <m>T \colon \mathbb{R}^n \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^n</m> be an invertible linear map.
			Then, if <m>E \subseteq \bR^n</m> is Lebesgue measurable, <m>T(E)</m> is Lebesgue measurable.
		</p>
	</statement>

	<proof>
	<p>
	Let <m>E \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> be a bounded Lebesgue measurable set. 
	By <xref ref="cor-Leb-meas-sets-G-delta-F-sigma"/> there is an <m>F_\sigma</m>-set <m>F \subseteq E</m> such that <m>m_n(E) = m_n(F) = 0</m>.
	Let <m>B = E\backslash F</m>. Then <m>m_n(B) = 0</m>.</p>
<p>Note that, since <m>T</m> is linear, <m>T^{-1}</m> is linear, and therefore continuous. Hence <m>T</m> sends closed sets to closed sets, and hence <m>F_\sigma</m> sets to <m>F_\sigma</m> sets.
	Further, since <m>T</m> is continuous, there is an <m>M \geq 0</m>, such that <m>\|T(x)\|_2 \leq M \|x\|_2</m>.
	Hence, <m>T</m> sends bounded sets to bounded sets.
	Hence <m>T(F)</m> is a bounded <m>F_\sigma</m> set.
	In particular, <m>T(F)</m> is Lebesgue measurable.
	</p>

	<p>
		By <xref ref="lem-meas-of-interval"/>,
		<md>
			m_n^*(T(B))\leq |\det(T)|m_n(B) = 0.
		</md>
		Hence, <m>m_n^*(T(B))=0</m>, and hence <m>T(B)</m> is Lebesgue measurable.
		Thus, 
		<md>
			T(E) = T(F) \cup T(B)
		</md>
		is Lebesgue measurable.
		As any measurable set is a countable union of bounded measurable sets, the result follows for all Lebesgue measurable sets.
	</p>
	</proof>
</lemma>


<proposition xml:id="prop-comp-meas-linear">
<p>Let <m>T \colon \mathbb{R}^n \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^n</m> be an invertible linear map and let <m>f</m> be a Lebesgue measurable function on <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>, then <m>f \circ T</m> is Lebesgue measurable.</p>
</proposition>
<proof>
<p>
 Take, <m>U \subseteq \bR</m> open.
 Since, <m>f</m> is measurable, <m>f^{-1}(U)</m> is a Lebesgue measurable set in <m>\bR^n</m>.
 By <xref ref="lem-lin-meas"/>, <m>T^{-1}(f^{-1}(U))</m> is a Lebesgue measurable set in <m>\bR^n</m>.
 Thus, <m>(f\circ T)^{-1}</m> is Lebesgue measurable.
</p>
</proof>

<p>We state now the main theorem of this section.
We delay the proof for now, to deal with some special cases.</p>

<theorem xml:id="thm-change-of-variables">
	<statement>
		<p>
			Let <m>T \colon \mathbb{R}^n \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^n</m> be an invertible linear map and let <m>f</m> be a Lebesgue integrable function on <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
			Then <m>f\circ T</m> is integrable and
			<md>
				\int_{\mathbb{R}^n} f\circ T \, d\mu = \frac{1}{\left|\det(T)\right|} \int_{\mathbb{R}^n} f \, d\mu.
			</md>
		</p>
	</statement>
</theorem>

<p>
	The proof of <xref ref="thm-change-of-variables"/> will ultimately follow an inductive argument.
	It suffices to show that the result holds for linear maps of <xref ref="li-type1" text="custom">Type 1</xref>, <xref ref="li-type2" text="custom">Type 2</xref>, and <xref ref="li-type3" text="custom">Type 3</xref>.
	We will prove the <m>n=1</m> and <m>n=2</m> cases first, and then use these cases to prove the general case.
	We leave the <m>n=1</m> case, <xref ref="lem-change-of-variables-n-1"/>, as an exercise.
</p>

<lemma xml:id="lem-change-of-variables-n-1">
	<statement>
		<p>
			Let <m>f \colon \bR \rightarrow \bR</m> be a Lebesgue integrable function.
			Then if <m>\alpha \in \bR</m> is non-zero,
			<md> \int_\bR f\,dm = |\alpha| \int_\bR f(\alpha x) \, dm(x). </md>
		</p>
	</statement>
</lemma>

<lemma xml:id="lem-change-of-variables-n-2">
	<statement>
		<p>
			Let <m>f \colon \bR^2 \rightarrow \bR</m> be a Lebesgue integrable function.
			Let <m>c \in \bR</m> be non-zero.
			Define functions <m>g,h,k</m> on <m>\bR^2</m> by
			<md>
				g(x,y) = f(y,x),\ h(x,y) = f(x,x+y),\text{ and } k(x,y) = f(cx,y).
			</md>
			Then <m>g,h,</m> and <m>k</m> are integrable, and
			<md>
				\int_{\bR^2} g \, dm_2 = \int_{\bR^2} h \, dm_2 = \int_{\bR^2} f \, dm_2,
			</md>
			and
			<md>
				\int_{\bR^2} k \, dm_2 = \frac{1}{|c|} \int_{\bR^2} f \, dm_2.
			</md>
		</p>
	</statement>

	<proof>
		<p>
			Note that <m>h,g,</m> and <m>k</m> are measurable by <xref ref="prop-comp-meas-linear"/>.
			We will prove the result for <m>h</m>.
			We will assume that <m>f</m> is non-negative.
			Then general case follows from writing <m>f</m> as the difference of its positive and negative parts.
			The proofs for <m>g</m> and <m>k</m> are similar, with an application of <xref ref="lem-change-of-variables-n-1"/> in the case of <m>k</m>.
			
			Note that, if <m>l \colon \bR \rightarrow \bR</m> is Lebesgue integrable and <m>\beta \in \bR</m> then
			<md>
				\int_\bR l(x+\beta)\,dm(x) = \int_\bR l\,dm.
			</md>
			By <xref ref="thm-tonelli" text="custom">Tonelli's theorem</xref>, we have that
			<md>
				<mrow> \int_{\bR^2}h\,dm_2 \amp = \int_\bR \int_\bR h(x,y)\, dm(y)dm(x) </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = \int_\bR \int_\bR f(x,x+y)\, dm(y)dm(x) </mrow> 
				<mrow> \amp = \int_\bR \int_\bR f(x,y)\, dm(y)dm(x). </mrow> 
			</md>
		</p>
	</proof>
</lemma>

<p>We can now prove <xref ref="thm-change-of-variables"/>.</p>

<proof><title>Proof of <xref ref="thm-change-of-variables"/></title>
<p>
	<xref ref="lem-change-of-variables-n-1"/> and <xref ref="lem-change-of-variables-n-2"/> show that the result holds for <m>n=1,2</m>.
	Assume now that <m>n\geq 3</m> and the result holds for <m>\bR^k</m> when <m>k&lt; n</m>.
	Assume that <m>T</m> is of <xref ref="li-type1" text="custom">Type 1</xref>, <xref ref="li-type2" text="custom">Type 2</xref>, and <xref ref="li-type3" text="custom">Type 3</xref>.
	Then, either <m>Te_1 = e_1</m> and <m>T \{(0,x_2,\ldots,x_n)\} \subseteq \{(0,x_2,\ldots,x_n)\}</m>, or <m>Te_n = e_n</m> and <m>T\{(x_1,x_2,\ldots,0)\} \subseteq \{(x_1,x_2,\ldots,0)\}</m>.
	Assume the former, the latter case is done similarly.
	Let <m>T'</m> be the restriction to the <m>n-1</m>-dimensional space <m>\{(0,x_2,\ldots,x_n)\} </m>.
	Then, by <xref ref="thm-fubini" text="custom">Fubini's Theorem</xref> (and <xref ref="prop-comp-meas-linear"/>)
	<md>
		<mrow>\int_\bR^n f\circ T \,dm_n \amp= \int_\bR \left( \int_{\bR^{n-1}} f(x_1, T'(x_2,\ldots,x_n)))\,dm_{n-1}\right)dm</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{|\det(T')|}\int_\bR \left( \int_{\bR^{n-1}} f(x_1, x_2,\ldots,x_n))\,dm_{n-1}\right)dm</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = \frac{1}{|\det(T')|}\int_\bR^n f \,dm_n.</mrow>
	</md>
	Noting that <m>\det(T) = \det(T')</m> completes the proof.
</p>
</proof>

</section>

<exercises>
<exercise xml:id="exer-sigma-finite-product">
<p>x	Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> and <m>(Y,\mathcal{N},\nu)</m> be <m>\sigma</m>-finite measure spaces. Show that the product measure <m>\mu\times \nu</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite on <m>X\times Y</m>.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-prod-meas-not-unique">
<p>Let <m>([0,1],\mathcal{M},m)</m> be the measure space consisting of the Lebesgue measure on the Lebesgue measurable subsets of <m>[0,1]</m>, and let <m>([0,1],\mathcal{M},c)</m> be the measure space of consisting of the counting measure on the Lebesgue measurable subsets of <m>[0,1]</m>.
	Let <m>\mathcal{N}</m> denote the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra of subsets of <m>[0,1]\times[0,1]</m> which are measurable with respect to the product measure <m>m\times c</m>.</p>
<p>For <m>E \in \mathcal{N}</m> and <m>y \in [0,1]</m>, let <m>E^y</m> be the <m>y</m>-section of <m>E</m>.
	Define a map <m>\sigma</m> on <m>\mathcal{N}</m> by
<md> \sigma(E) = \sum_{y\in[0,1]} m(E^y)</md>
(See <xref ref="lem-uncountable-series"/> and the preceding paragraphs for information on series of sets indexed by uncountable sets).</p>
<ol>
<li><p>Show that <m>\sigma</m> is a measure on <m>([0,1]\times[0,1],\mathcal{N})</m>.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Show that <m>\sigma(A\times B)=m(A)c(B)</m> for all <m>A,B \in \mathcal{M}</m>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>Let <m>D = \{(x,x) \colon x \in [0,1]\}</m>.
	Note that
<md>D = \bigcap_{n=1}^\infty \bigcup_{k=1}^n \left[\frac{k-1}{n},\frac{k}{n} \right] \times \left[\frac{k-1}{n},\frac{k}{n} \right],</md>
and hence <m>D \in \mathcal{M}</m>.
<ol>
<li>Show that <m>\sigma(D) = 0</m>.
</li>
<li>Show that <m>(m\times c)(D)=\infty</m>.
		(Hint: show that if <m>\{A_k\times B_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> are measurable rectangles such that <m>D \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty A_k \times B_k</m>, then
		<md>\sum_{k=1}^\infty m(A_k)c(B_k) = \infty.)</md>
</li>
</ol>
We have thus given an example of a measure <m>\sigma</m> on <m>[0,1]\times[0,1]</m> which agrees with the product measure <m>m\times c</m> on measurable rectangles, but is not equal to the product measure.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-product-measurable-sets">
<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> and <m>(Y,\mathcal{N},\nu)</m> be measure spaces.</p>
<ol>
<li><p>Let <m>\mathcal{L}</m> be the collection of sets <m>F \subseteq X\times Y</m> such that the <m>x</m>-section <m>F_x\in \mathcal{N}</m> for all <m>x \in X</m>.
		Show that <m>\mathcal{L}</m> is a <m>\sigma</m>-algebra.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Show that if <m>E \subseteq X\times Y</m> is in the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra generated by the measurable rectangles, then the <m>x</m>-section <m>E_x \in \mathcal{N}</m> for all <m>x \in X</m>.
		(HINT: Show that the measurable rectangles are in the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra <m>\mathcal{L}</m>.)</p>
</li>
<li><p>Take non-empty <m>A \in \mathcal{M}</m> such that <m>\mu(A)=0</m>; and take <m>B \subseteq Y</m> which is not measurable, i.e. <m>B\notin \mathcal{N}</m>.
		
		Show that <m>A\times B</m> is measurable with respect to the product measure <m>\mu\times \nu</m>.
		Show that <m>A\times B</m> is not in <m>\mathcal{L}</m>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-meas-rect-sigma-alg">
<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> and <m>(Y,\mathcal{N},\nu)</m> be <m>\sigma</m>-finite measure spaces and let <m>\mathcal{F}</m> be the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra of subsets of <m>X \times Y</m> generated by the measurable rectangles.
		In this exercise we will prove, for all <m>E \in \mathcal{F}</m>, that the map <m>x \mapsto \nu(E_x)</m> is measurable and
<md number="yes" xml:id="eq-meas-rect-sigma-alg">
(\mu\times \nu)(E) = \int_X \nu(E_x)\,d\mu.
</md>
We will do this over several parts.</p>
<p>For <m>E \in \mathcal{F}</m>, define a map <m>\Phi_E</m> on <m>X</m>, by <m>\Phi_E(x)= \nu(E_x)</m>.		
		Let <m>\mathcal{S}</m> be all the measurable rectangles in <m>X \times Y</m>; let <m>\mathcal{S}'</m> be all finite unions of disjoint sets in <m>\mathcal{S}</m>; let <m>\mathcal{C}</m> be the smallest collection of subsets containing <m>\mathcal{S}</m> which is closed under countable unions and countable intersections; and let <m>\mathcal{G}</m> be the collection of sets <m>E \in \mathcal{F}</m> for which <m>\Phi_E</m> is measurable and  <xref ref="eq-meas-rect-sigma-alg"/> holds.
<ol>
<li>Note that if <m>E \in \mathcal{F}</m>, then the <m>x</m>-section <m>E_x</m> is measurable for all <m>x \in X</m>. Hence <m>\Phi_E</m> is defined on all <m>x \in X</m>. (HINT: This is already done in <xref ref="exer-product-measurable-sets"/>).
</li>
<li>Show that <m>\mathcal{S} \subseteq \mathcal{G}</m>. (HINT: This is already done in <xref ref="lem-prod-meas-as-integral"/> when <m>(\mu\times\nu)(E)&lt;\infty</m>. What needs to change in the argument if <m>(\mu\times\nu)(E)=\infty</m>?).
</li>
<li>Show that <m>\mathcal{G}</m> is closed under countable unions.
</li>
</ol>
Until we state otherwise, we will now assume that <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> and <m>(Y,\mathcal{N},\nu)</m> are finite measure spaces.</p>
<p>
<ol>
<li>Show that <m>\mathcal{G}</m> is closed under countable intersections.
</li>
<li>Conclude that <m>\mathcal{C} \subseteq \mathcal{G}</m>.
</li>
</ol>
For <m>E \in \mathcal{C}</m> let
<md> \mathcal{C}(E) = \{ F \in \mathcal{C} \colon E \cap F,\, E\backslash F,\, F \backslash E \in \mathcal{C}\}.</md>
<ol>
<li>Show that <m>\mathcal{S}' \subseteq \mathcal{C}</m>.
</li>
<li>Show that for each <m>E \in \mathcal{C}</m>, <m>\mathcal{C}(E)</m> is closed under countable unions and countable intersections.
</li>
<li xml:id="part-meas-rect-sigma-alg"> Show that if <m>E \in \mathcal{S}'</m>, then <m>\mathcal{S}' \subseteq \mathcal{C}(E)</m> (HINT: Recall <xref ref="lem-Car-ext-2" />). Conclude that <m>\mathcal{C}(E) = \mathcal{C}</m>.
</li>
<li><p>Show that if <m>F \in \mathcal{C}</m>, then <m>\mathcal{C}(F)= \mathcal{C}</m>. (Consider the symmetry in definition of <m>\mathcal{C}(E)</m> and part~\ref{part: meas rect sigma-alg}.)</p>
</li>
<li><p>Show that <m>\mathcal{C}</m> is closed under complements, finite unions, and finite intersections.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Show that <m>\mathcal{C}</m> is closed under countable unions. Conclude that <m>\mathcal{C}</m> is a <m>\sigma</m>-algebra.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Conclude that <m>\mathcal{C} = \mathcal{F}</m>, and hence <m>\mathcal{G} = \mathcal{F}</m>.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Assume now that <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> and <m>(Y,\mathcal{N},\nu)</m> are <m>\sigma</m>-finite measure spaces. Show that <m>\mathcal{G} = \mathcal{F}</m>.</p>
</li>
</ol></p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-failure-of-fubini">
<p>Let <m>([0,1],\mathcal{M},m)</m> be the measure space consisting of the Lebesgue measure on the Lebesgue measurable subsets of <m>[0,1]</m>; let <m>([0,1],\mathcal{M},c)</m> be the measure space of consisting of the counting measure on the Lebesgue measurable subsets of <m>[0,1]</m>; and let <m>D = \{(x,x) \colon x \in [0,1]\}</m>.</p>
<p>Show that
<md> \int_{[0,1]\times[0,1]} \chi_D\,d(m\times c) \neq \int_{[0,1]}\left(\int_{[0,1]} \chi_D(x,y)\,dc(y)\right)dm(x).</md>
Why does this not contradict Fubini's Theorem? Why does this not contradict Tonelli's Theorem?
		(HINT: The first part of this question is essentially a rephrasing of <xref ref="exer-prod-meas-not-unique"/>.)</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-measurable-rectangles-2">
<p>Let <m>\{(X_K,\mathcal{M}_k,\mu_k)\}_{k=1}^n</m> be measure spaces, let <m>\mathcal{S}</m> be the measurable rectangles in <m>\prod_{k=1}^n X_k</m>.
	Show that <m>\mathcal{S}</m> is a semiring.</p>
<p>Note that this exercise completes part of the proof of <xref ref="prop-n-dim-prod-measure"/>.
	The remainder is proved in <xref ref="exer-n-dim-prod-measure"/>.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-n-dim-prod-measure">
<p>Let <m>\{(X_K,\mathcal{M}_k,\mu_k)\}_{k=1}^n</m> be measure spaces, let <m>\mathcal{S}</m> be the measurable rectangles in <m>\prod_{k=1}^n X_k</m>; and let <m>\mu_1 \times \ldots \times \mu_n</m> be the extended real-valued function on <m>\mathcal{S}</m> defined by
<md> (\mu_1 \times \ldots \times \mu_n)(A_1\times \ldots \times A_n) = \mu_1(A_1)\mu_2(A_2)\ldots \mu_n(A_n)</md>
for <m>A_k \in \mathcal{M}_k</m> for <m>1\leq k \leq n</m>.
	Show that <m>\mu_1 \times \ldots \times\mu_n</m> is a premeasure on <m>\mathcal{S}</m>.</p>
<p>Note that this exercise completes part of the proof of <xref ref="prop-n-dim-prod-measure"/>.
	The first part is proved in <xref ref="exer-measurable-rectangles-2" />.</p>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exer-triangle">
	<task xml:id="exer-triangle-a"><statement>
		<p>Let <m>a,b>0</m> be real numbers. Let
		<md>
			\Delta = \{(x,y) \colon 0\leq x \leq a,\ 0\leq y\leq \frac{b}{a}x\}.
		</md>
		Show that <m>m_2(\Delta) = ab/2</m>. (HINT: Cover <m>\Delta</m> with rectangles, and use the continuity of measure).
		</p>
	</statement></task>
	<task>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Let <m>\Delta</m> be a triangular region in <m>\bR^2</m> with one side parallel to the <m>x</m>-axis or <m>y</m>-axis.
				Show that <m>m_2(\Delta)=ab/2</m>, where <m>a</m> is the length of a side parallel to an axis, and <m>b</m> is the perpendicular distance to the opposite vertex. (HINT: <xref ref="exer-triangle-a" text="custom">Part (a)</xref> deals with right-angle triangles. Other right-angle triangles can be dealt with similarly. For arbitrary <m>\Delta</m>, write <m>\Delta</m> as the union or difference of two right-angle triangles.)
			</p>
		</statement>
	</task>

	<task>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Let <m>P</m> be a parallelogram in <m>\bR^2</m> with one (and hence two) sides parallel to the <m>y</m>-axis. Show that if the length of the sides parallel to the <m>y</m>-axis is <m>a</m> and the perpendicular distance between these sides is <m>b</m>, then <m>m_2(P) = ab</m>.
			</p>
		</statement>
	</task>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exer-borel-in-Rn">
<p>Prove <xref ref="prop-borel-in-Rn" />.
	That is, show that is <m>B</m> is a Borel subset of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> then <m>B</m> is Lebesgue measurable.
	(HINT: First show that open subsets of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> are Lebesgue measurable.)</p>
</exercise>
</exercises>
</chapter>
